The paper focuses on developing piecewise linear spiking neuron models that can reproduce different behaviors similar to biological neurons, and investigates their digital implementation feasibility and costs for large-scale hardware implementation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Additionally, the paper also discusses the use of these models for character recognition, which falls under the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of FPGA for hardware synthesis and physical implementation, which suggests that it could belong to the Embedded Systems (cs.ET) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper also discusses the use of spike rate coding, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
